    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Presidential Candidates Jockey for Position in Campaign Fund-Raising Sweepstakes'' (news article, March 30):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Presidential Candidates Jockey for Position in Campaign Fund-Raising Sweepstakes'' (news article, March 30):</p>
        <p>Do you have to jump on board the dollars-accumulated test for success? To be sure, money will once again have an inordinate effect on the campaign. It will be a major factor -- perhaps the major factor. And one cannot win a national election in this country without a war chest.</p>
        <p>But in large part it has been the media that have decided that early fund-raising should be given the kind of status that can sway consideration away from the best candidates.</p>
        <p>Unceasingly reporting on early ''returns'' in fund-raising simply ensures that the wealthy will continue to get a head start in any election and that legitimate candidates will be foreclosed by the panic of contributors trying to rush to a winner.</p>
        <p>Why not give us an article headlined ''Who Will Buy Our Government This Time?'' and then analyzing why we allow this to be so?</p>
        <p>Thomas E. Dixon Jr.  Madison, Wis., March 31, 2007</p>
      </block>
